To set a GRUB password, follow these steps
Generate a Password Hash:
Open a terminal and run the following command to generate a hashed password:
[root@linuxtestserver ~]# grub2-mkpasswd-pbkdf2
Enter password:
Reenter password:
PBKDF2 hash of your password is grub.pbkdf2.sha512.10000.28D609CA6FC2019A8AF8A6CCE76299DE0D86379F59D8E03DB8D6A10AE13D730ABE52D6D57C79A18984402A781EB5864881C58EC13936D9210D52D37E68909637.4310D2CF98021F54D087C847E950FD06759ADD33F23637E4A87712C61D39B46F33C0A3D4092053160927DD20C5291C59C0D580B1F76F537D92D70939098A5207
[root@linuxtestserver ~]# vi /etc/grub.d/40_custom
Add the following lines to set the superuser and password:
set superusers="root"
password_pbkdf2 root grub.pbkdf2.sha512.10000.28D609CA6FC2019A8AF8A6CCE76299DE0D86379F59D8E03DB8D6A10AE13D730ABE52D6D57C79A18984402A781EB5864881C58EC13936D9210D52D37E68909637.4310D2CF98021F54D087C847E950FD06759ADD33F23637E4A87712C61D39B46F33C0A3D4092053160927DD20C5291C59C0D580B1F76F537D92D70939098A5207

# grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
# reboot
*** Recovery ***
Boot into Rescue Mode using rhel CD.
Insert the RHEL installation media and boot from it.
Select the "Troubleshooting" option and then "Rescue a Red Hat Enterprise Linux system".
The system will attempt to find your Linux installation and mount it under /mnt/sysimage.
# chroot /mnt/sysimage
# grub2-mkpasswd-pbkdf2 ## generate new password.
# vi /etc/grub.d/40_custom  ## upadte hash password, also we can remove it.
set superusers="root"
password_pbkdf2 root <new-hashed-password>

# grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg Exit the chroot environment by typing exit.
Reboot your system: reboot.
